# Cursor Rule: Flutter Coding Style (ff-app)

## 1) Architecture alignment guardrails
- Follow Riverpod-first flow: no BLoC/get_it patterns for new work.
- Follow layered boundaries: `ui/ -> app/ -> domain/ -> infra/`.
- Keep IO and side effects out of widgets.

## 2) Design system usage (mandatory)
- Use `AppTypography` for text styles.
- Use `LayoutConstants` for spacing, paddings, and dimensions.
- Avoid introducing raw UI literals when a design token exists.

## 3) Naming consistency
- Files: `snake_case.dart` and descriptive by responsibility.
- Classes/types/enums/extensions: `PascalCase`.
- Variables/params/functions/methods: `camelCase`.
- Constants: `lowerCamelCase` for private consts, `UPPER_SNAKE_CASE` only for true global compile-time constants.
- Booleans must read as predicates (`isConnected`, `hasError`, `canRetry`).
- Async methods should be verb-first and explicit (`fetchPlaylists`, `loadChannelById`, `saveWork`).

## 4) Commenting policy (in-file comments favored)
- Prefer in-file comments over separate docs when explaining behavior, constraints, and architectural intent.
- Favor descriptive comments that explain:
  - why the code exists
  - what constraints or invariants it preserves
  - what can break if changed
  - integration assumptions (FF1 state, transport/protocol expectations, DP-1 mapping)
- Add comments at non-obvious boundaries: provider orchestration, conversions, concurrency, retries, and fallback logic.
- Avoid noisy comments that only restate syntax.

## 5) Dartdoc policy (official guidance)
Based on Dart documentation (`dart.dev`), apply these key points:
- Use `///` Dartdoc for all public APIs and any private member with non-trivial behavior.
- Start docs with a one-line summary sentence, then details on behavior and constraints.
- Document parameters, return behavior, and side effects in prose.
- Use square-bracket references for symbols (for example `[Playlist]`, `[ProviderContainer]`).
- Document thrown exceptions/failure modes and state assumptions when relevant.
- Include short usage examples for complex APIs when it improves correctness.

## 6) Testing-minded implementation style
- Prefer small single-responsibility functions that are straightforward to unit test.
- Keep pure logic in `domain/` or pure helpers; inject dependencies for side-effecting code.
- Do not merge feature flow code before core unit/integration tests are in place (see `.cursor/rules/35-testing-tdd.mdc`).

## 7) Quality gates before completion
- `flutter analyze` must pass.
- `flutter test` must pass.
- New code must not increase lint debt.
